WEBVTT

00:13.013 --> 00:14.549
(MAN SNIFFLING)

00:32.741 --> 00:34.242
A lot of us
are still in shock

00:34.326 --> 00:36.817
about the tragic events
that have brought us here.

00:37.913 --> 00:42.202
The loss of
Walter and Susan Perkins

00:42.251 --> 00:45.243
forces us to question
if the work we do

00:45.879 --> 00:47.665
is worth the risks.

00:48.507 --> 00:51.214
Eureka was born
from the idealistic vision

00:51.260 --> 00:53.216
that by advancing science,

00:53.345 --> 00:56.007
we can control it
for the greater good.

00:56.807 --> 00:59.298
Clearly,
that's not always the case.

00:59.434 --> 01:01.686
We can never forget
Walter and Susan.

01:01.728 --> 01:03.593
Their legacy
is in our hands now.

01:03.689 --> 01:06.396
Their friends, their family.

01:07.067 --> 01:08.398
Their son.

01:14.950 --> 01:18.158
Walter and Susan,
you will be greatly missed.

02:04.750 --> 02:06.160
ALLISON:
I still don't get it.

02:06.251 --> 02:09.038
CARTER: What's that?
Susan committing suicide.

02:09.129 --> 02:10.994
I mean,
I know it sounds callous,

02:11.089 --> 02:12.420
but I don't care
how bad things are,

02:12.466 --> 02:15.799
once you have a kid,
you don't
get to just check out.

02:16.094 --> 02:17.174
Well.

02:17.596 --> 02:19.632
My daughter Zoe said
pretty much
the same thing to me

02:19.723 --> 02:22.681
when I told her l was
being transferred to Eureka.

02:22.768 --> 02:26.056
Taking your life
and taking a job
are hardly the same thing.

02:26.146 --> 02:27.477
In this town?

02:27.981 --> 02:29.221
Not so sure.

02:40.619 --> 02:42.155
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)

02:42.245 --> 02:43.701
(SIGHING) Oh.

02:51.463 --> 02:52.498
(HORN HONKING)

02:52.589 --> 02:54.329
(CAR ALARM SOUNDING)

03:03.600 --> 03:05.056
(CROW CAWING)

03:08.939 --> 03:10.679
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

03:11.483 --> 03:15.226
I don't need you to tell me
that I don't have a place
to put my stuff.

03:15.320 --> 03:16.696
I know that!

03:18.740 --> 03:19.855
(PHONE RINGING)
Well, the question is,

03:19.950 --> 03:22.987
where is my stuff that
I don't have anywhere to put?

03:23.036 --> 03:24.367
Lupo.
Yeah, yeah, I know.

03:24.454 --> 03:25.864
Tracking numbers
and corporate policy,

03:25.956 --> 03:26.945
but there's a...
It's for you.

03:27.040 --> 03:28.155
Yeah, could you
take a message, please?

03:28.208 --> 03:30.039
No. It sounds urgent.

03:30.711 --> 03:31.951
Hang on.

03:32.379 --> 03:34.119
Hello, Jack Carter.

03:35.549 --> 03:36.664
Really?

03:37.092 --> 03:38.832
A ghost. Very mature.

03:40.262 --> 03:41.877
Look, it's very convincing,
but I get it,

03:41.972 --> 03:44.714
haze the new guy, big laughs.
I gotta go.

03:45.225 --> 03:46.590
Hello, yeah.

03:47.936 --> 03:49.847
Hello? You still there?

03:50.021 --> 03:51.397
Oh, come on.

03:54.568 --> 03:56.399
Great. Thank you, Jo.

03:56.820 --> 03:58.936
I think I may have lost
my only chance
of getting my stuff back

03:59.030 --> 04:01.567
because I had to
take a crank call
about a haunting.

04:01.616 --> 04:03.322
ldidn't set that up.
Yeah?

04:03.410 --> 04:06.072
I should believe you, why?

04:06.663 --> 04:10.201
Carter,
this is a town
full of scientists.

04:10.417 --> 04:13.284
Everyone knows there's
no such thing as ghosts.

04:13.378 --> 04:14.914
(DOOR OPENING)

04:15.088 --> 04:16.953
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

04:17.340 --> 04:18.841
(DOOR CLOSING)

04:21.386 --> 04:23.377
Where is Walter?

04:32.898 --> 04:33.978
Um...

04:34.983 --> 04:36.393
You were saying?

05:16.733 --> 05:19.475
CARTER:
I'm not sure this will all
get worked out, Mrs. Perkins.

05:19.569 --> 05:21.605
I need to see Walter now.

05:21.988 --> 05:24.650
Walter was obviously trying
to hurt me. And when l...

05:25.450 --> 05:27.862
What?
What are you
all staring at?

05:29.037 --> 05:31.244
Sorry if we seem
a little unnerved,

05:31.331 --> 05:33.822
but we just buried you
this morning.

05:34.835 --> 05:36.450
You're unnerved?

05:36.753 --> 05:38.664
My parents called me
in hysterics,

05:38.713 --> 05:40.578
because they got
an invitation to my funeral,

05:40.674 --> 05:44.007
and a message saying
that they had a grandson
who needs a home.

05:44.052 --> 05:45.508
Which was all
a big surprise to me,

05:45.595 --> 05:49.053
seeing as how I'm not dead
and I've never had a child.

05:50.141 --> 05:51.642
Yeah, you win.

05:52.310 --> 05:54.016
We're just trying
to figure out
what's going on.

05:54.104 --> 05:56.595
Then get Walter in here
and ask him.

05:57.065 --> 05:58.896
You didn't tell her?
l was getting to it.

05:58.984 --> 06:01.600
"Tell her" what?
Walter's dead.

06:03.446 --> 06:04.652
Walter's dead?

06:04.698 --> 06:08.941
(STUTTERING) Yeah, he sort of,
blew himself up.

06:10.036 --> 06:11.367
Oh, my God.

06:11.663 --> 06:13.699
(STUTTERING)
What? You're notjoking?

06:13.748 --> 06:15.363
I'm sorry, Susan.

06:16.459 --> 06:17.539
Hold on.

06:17.586 --> 06:20.202
If she's Susan Perkins,
then who did we...

06:22.382 --> 06:23.667
You're staring again.

06:23.717 --> 06:26.550
Yeah, do you mind
if I ask you
how you and Walter met?

06:27.762 --> 06:31.721
l was a grad student at MIT.
He was a post-doc.

06:32.851 --> 06:35.433
We got married
right after graduation,

06:36.396 --> 06:38.728
and he wanted
to start a family,

06:39.524 --> 06:40.934
but I wasn't ready.

06:41.026 --> 06:43.768
One morning
this guy came to the door

06:43.862 --> 06:47.320
and wanted
to talk to Walter
about some top-secret job.

06:47.741 --> 06:50.232
He wanted to go,
I wanted to stay.

06:51.578 --> 06:53.193
So we separated.

06:54.748 --> 06:56.704
You do realize we are
gonna have to verify that

06:56.750 --> 06:58.365
so we can
sort this thing out.

06:58.418 --> 07:00.079
How long is that gonna take?

07:00.170 --> 07:01.250
I'm not really sure.

07:01.338 --> 07:03.920
It's not like we have
a standard form to undead you.

07:03.965 --> 07:05.080
(CLEARING THROAT)

07:05.133 --> 07:06.213
Tell me you're kidding.

07:06.259 --> 07:08.671
924/B. ln triplicate.

07:09.638 --> 07:11.424
We'll still need
to confirm your identity.

07:11.473 --> 07:13.964
How are you gonna do that?
We're gonna do a DNA test.

07:14.059 --> 07:15.674
Oh, we can do
better than that.

07:15.769 --> 07:18.761
But we're still gonna
need to do some digging.

07:18.980 --> 07:21.767
Oh, you mean
I gotta go back to the...
Yes.

07:21.983 --> 07:23.894
Well, someone's gotta
get me a coroner.
That's right.

07:23.944 --> 07:26.060
Just do
what you have to do.

07:26.112 --> 07:28.364
I just wanna get back
to my normal life.

07:28.448 --> 07:29.984
Yeah, I can relate.

07:33.036 --> 07:34.276
(SIGHING)

07:45.632 --> 07:47.964
County Coroner, huh?
Board certified.

07:49.761 --> 07:50.796
Oh.

07:58.812 --> 07:59.972
Pretty cool, huh?

08:00.021 --> 08:02.478
I call it
an Omniversal Remote.

08:02.524 --> 08:04.765
I can run all this equipment
by remote control.

08:04.818 --> 08:07.730
That's super, Henry.
Can we just hurry it up?

08:07.821 --> 08:09.732
I'm not a big
fan of cemeteries.

08:09.823 --> 08:12.735
Oh. One too many
Romero movies, huh?

08:12.826 --> 08:14.862
One too many funerals.

08:15.870 --> 08:16.996
(ALARM SOUNDING)

08:17.080 --> 08:18.286
Oh! Oh!

08:18.873 --> 08:20.283
That's crazy.

08:20.333 --> 08:23.325
I mean, something's
actually interfering
with the frequency.

08:23.378 --> 08:24.618
(BUZZING)

08:24.671 --> 08:25.706
(DIS TOR TED)
Pull the batteries!

08:25.797 --> 08:26.877
What?

08:27.298 --> 08:29.004
Pull the battery!

08:29.050 --> 08:30.551
(ALARM STOPS)

08:31.845 --> 08:33.335
Ought to keep things quiet.

08:33.430 --> 08:34.966
I guess I got
a few more kinks to work out.

08:35.015 --> 08:36.095
Hmm.

08:37.183 --> 08:39.014
Well, just see
if you can get the body

08:39.102 --> 08:42.344
to Global Dynamics
without alerting
the entire town.

08:42.856 --> 08:45.188
I'm going over there now
to see Allison.

08:47.277 --> 08:48.608
Batteries.

08:49.195 --> 08:51.527
Now, why didn't
I think of that?

09:04.044 --> 09:07.207
MAN: Global Dynamics,
Satellite Five,
online in three.

09:07.297 --> 09:10.710
Global Dynamics,
Satellite Five,
online in three.

09:10.759 --> 09:12.420
(MACHINE STARTING)

09:17.307 --> 09:18.672
So you met
the new director yet?

09:18.725 --> 09:20.932
Not yet. He just arrived.

09:21.019 --> 09:23.101
Global Dynamics
is under DARPAjurisdiction

09:23.188 --> 09:25.520
and they get a little crazy
about sharing information.

09:25.565 --> 09:27.226
Hence our visit.
What's DARPA?

09:27.317 --> 09:29.649
The Defense Advanced
Research Project Agency.

09:29.736 --> 09:32.068
It's the central research arm
of the DOD.

09:32.113 --> 09:33.728
Okay, so why am I here?

09:33.823 --> 09:35.814
Well, you wanna use
the new molecular bio-scanner

09:35.909 --> 09:38.571
on Susan Perkins' body
and this new woman, right?

09:38.620 --> 09:39.700
Maybe.

09:39.746 --> 09:41.953
Yeah. Well, all requests
to use laboratory resources

09:42.040 --> 09:45.703
for police applications
must be submitted
to the Director of Research.

09:45.752 --> 09:48.084
Who we haven't met yet.
Exactly.

09:50.173 --> 09:51.379
Nathan?

09:52.550 --> 09:55.257
Allison. I swear
I was just about
to call you.

09:55.303 --> 09:57.464
What are you doing here?
You're not...

09:57.555 --> 09:59.637
Afraid so.
You're moving
back to Eureka?

09:59.724 --> 10:01.589
Moved, actually. Yesterday.

10:01.643 --> 10:04.726
Same office, same house.
Surprise!

10:08.608 --> 10:11.520
I probably
should've called sooner.
Probably.

10:12.278 --> 10:14.018
You must be
the new sheriff
I've heard so much about.

10:14.114 --> 10:16.105
Nathan Stark.
Jack Carter.

10:17.283 --> 10:19.114
So, you two
used to work together?

10:19.202 --> 10:20.533
I mainly work
with her son Kevin,

10:20.620 --> 10:22.952
but Allie and I
had our moments.

10:25.792 --> 10:28.204
Anyway, I was looking
into something

10:28.294 --> 10:33.163
and wanted to know
if! could use your
bio scanner-molecule-thingy.

10:33.508 --> 10:35.044
Of course,
anything I can do to help.

10:35.135 --> 10:37.626
(CLEARING THROAT)
Excuse me, Dr. Stark.

10:37.720 --> 10:39.676
Maggie's taking care
of your parking space

10:39.764 --> 10:42.631
and the new furniture
will be delivered tomorrow.

10:42.725 --> 10:44.386
A lot to catch up on.

10:44.477 --> 10:47.093
Sheriff, it's been a pleasure.
Allison,

10:48.857 --> 10:50.643
it's good to see you.

10:58.700 --> 11:00.565
So you two have a history?

11:00.660 --> 11:01.820
You could say that.

11:01.870 --> 11:04.077
What, ex-boyfriend?
Not exactly.

11:04.164 --> 11:06.655
Well, what exactly?
He's my husband.

11:12.672 --> 11:14.833
SUSAN: Thanks for
letting me stay with you.

11:15.300 --> 11:16.506
Just don't tell the sheriff

11:16.551 --> 11:18.667
that I've got
a spare bedroom, okay?

11:21.806 --> 11:23.182
Oh, my God!

11:23.516 --> 11:25.017
What, did you see something?

11:25.059 --> 11:27.596
If you did,
there's this form that I
gotta get you to sign, so...

11:27.687 --> 11:31.020
No. It's our house.
Wait. Pull over.

11:38.031 --> 11:41.694
This is your house.
I mean, Susan Perkins' house.

11:41.784 --> 11:42.864
But how did you know?

11:42.911 --> 11:44.367
Before Walter and I split up,

11:44.412 --> 11:47.529
we were planning to
build our dream home.

11:49.042 --> 11:50.407
This is it.

11:59.969 --> 12:02.585
(EXCLAIMING)
lt's exactly the same.

12:06.559 --> 12:07.935
(EXCLAIMING)

12:09.812 --> 12:12.019
I even picked that wallpaper.

12:16.110 --> 12:17.646
This is unreal!

12:20.073 --> 12:21.609
It's me, but...

12:23.409 --> 12:24.865
But it isn't.

12:27.163 --> 12:28.824
This is their son?

12:29.457 --> 12:32.494
Hey, Susan,
maybe this isn't
such a good idea.

12:36.381 --> 12:38.337
This can't be happening.

12:41.010 --> 12:42.216
Kevin.

12:42.262 --> 12:44.594
Honey, five more minutes,
then it's time for bed, okay?

12:44.681 --> 12:46.592
Five minutes.

12:46.933 --> 12:49.925
300 seconds. 7:30 pm.

12:50.687 --> 12:52.427
How does he do that?

12:53.523 --> 12:57.015
Well, his brain just works
differently than other people.

13:01.447 --> 13:03.278
I miss my mom and dad.

13:05.868 --> 13:09.156
I know, honey, it's hard
to lose the people we love.

13:09.956 --> 13:11.947
But, it does get better.

13:12.292 --> 13:15.784
And the important thing
to remember is that
they loved you very much.

13:19.549 --> 13:21.665
My mom dropped me at school.

13:21.843 --> 13:24.175
She said
she'd be back to get me,

13:24.554 --> 13:27.466
but she never came.

13:30.977 --> 13:33.969
I know she would've
been there if she could've.

13:34.355 --> 13:35.470
Okay?

13:36.316 --> 13:38.648
Tomorrow's gonna be
a better day.

13:42.613 --> 13:43.864
(SlGHlNG)

14:32.246 --> 14:34.032
(CARTER MOANING)

14:40.254 --> 14:41.790
(DOOR OPENING)

14:42.173 --> 14:43.834
(HINGES SQUEAKING)

15:00.233 --> 15:02.224
Freeze! Don't move!

15:04.737 --> 15:06.728
Evening, Sheriff Carter.

15:07.740 --> 15:09.196
Fargo. How...

15:10.284 --> 15:11.740
I thought I locked the door.

15:11.786 --> 15:13.947
(STUTTERING)
Yeah, no. It doesn't work.

15:14.038 --> 15:16.370
Sheriff Cobb always
had an open door policy.

15:16.416 --> 15:17.701
(SlGHlNG)

15:17.792 --> 15:20.249
You might wanna be
careful with this.

15:20.336 --> 15:21.746
It's a portable generator.

15:21.838 --> 15:25.706
S0?
A fission-powered
portable generator.

15:26.634 --> 15:29.250
Okay. Don't sleep on
the nuclear powered device.

15:29.303 --> 15:30.918
Good safety tip.

15:34.016 --> 15:37.099
Fargo, what do you want?
It's 10:30 at night.

15:37.895 --> 15:39.556
Actually,
I'm here to help you.

15:39.605 --> 15:41.561
I heard you were looking
for a place to stay,

15:41.607 --> 15:44.064
and I'm involved in

15:44.569 --> 15:47.436
a little project that
I think you may find
interesting.

15:47.530 --> 15:48.736
Really?

15:50.283 --> 15:52.114
What kind of project?

15:55.621 --> 15:56.781
Almost there.

15:56.831 --> 15:58.947
Can I open my eyes yet?
Okay.

16:02.211 --> 16:05.294
Behold.
The home of the future.

16:14.390 --> 16:15.630
Come on!

16:15.808 --> 16:17.264
(DOOR OPENING)

16:18.478 --> 16:20.594
All right, watch your step.

16:24.484 --> 16:26.600
(CARTER SIGHING)

16:32.950 --> 16:35.157
I'm going back to my cell.
Oh, come on, Sheriff.

16:35.244 --> 16:36.495
Just take a look.

16:36.537 --> 16:38.994
I know she's not much
from the outside,
but I promise,

16:39.040 --> 16:41.622
once you get
to know SARAH,
you'll love her.

16:42.502 --> 16:43.867
Who's Sarah?

16:44.295 --> 16:46.160
SARAH, open door.

16:46.339 --> 16:49.672
Fargo, I don't know
if this is a good idea...

16:53.471 --> 16:55.086
Lights, moderate.

16:58.518 --> 17:01.351
Music, jazz, soft.

17:03.189 --> 17:04.929
(MUSIC PLAYING)

17:05.024 --> 17:06.355
Fireplace.

17:10.112 --> 17:11.693
SARAH: Welcome.

17:11.781 --> 17:14.773
Okay, what's that?
That was SARAH.

17:15.952 --> 17:18.864
Self-Actuated Residential
Automated Habitat.

17:18.913 --> 17:20.369
SARAH for short.

17:21.874 --> 17:23.080
Fargo?

17:23.876 --> 17:26.208
Is that you
talking like a girl?

17:26.629 --> 17:29.211
No, it's the Smart House.

17:29.257 --> 17:30.622
A state-of—the-art
model home

17:30.716 --> 17:34.254
designed to anticipate
its owner's every need
and desire.

17:34.887 --> 17:36.468
Of course,
it'll take some time

17:36.556 --> 17:38.888
to learn all of
your personal preferences.

17:38.933 --> 17:40.264
Well,
my preference right now

17:40.351 --> 17:42.387
is to have a house
that isn't radioactive.

17:42.478 --> 17:45.094
(SNICKERS)
Well, it used to be
a nuclear disaster bunker.

17:45.189 --> 17:47.601
But don't worry,
the rad levels are
well within normal.

17:47.692 --> 17:49.148
That's great.

17:51.028 --> 17:52.404
The telecommunications system

17:52.488 --> 17:54.103
is linked directly
to your office.

17:54.198 --> 17:58.066
And the skeleton profile
has been programmed
into the mainframe.

17:59.662 --> 18:00.902
Bathroom.

18:01.247 --> 18:04.080
Oh, Fargo, you gotta
get yourself a girlfriend.

18:04.125 --> 18:07.834
There's a 24-hour helpline
if you run into any problems.

18:07.920 --> 18:09.296
SARAH, door.

18:11.340 --> 18:13.080
I'll come check in on you
tomorrow.

18:13.134 --> 18:14.294
Fargo.

18:15.052 --> 18:17.543
If this house is so great,
why is it sitting here vacant?

18:17.597 --> 18:19.588
SARAH, door.
Sleep tight.

18:20.474 --> 18:22.430
Oh, no.

18:26.564 --> 18:27.849
(SIGHING)

18:29.275 --> 18:31.140
I'm a human guinea pig.

18:34.655 --> 18:36.270
(CLEARING THROAT)

18:42.204 --> 18:44.411
SO, SARAH, is it?

18:44.832 --> 18:47.289
SARAH: That's correct,
Sheriff Carter.

18:47.335 --> 18:48.541
Uh-huh.

18:49.795 --> 18:52.832
Can you see me?
Yes, Sheriff Carter.

18:55.635 --> 18:56.920
Terrific.

18:58.596 --> 19:00.382
I'm gonna need a drink.

19:08.522 --> 19:10.183
(CLICKING TONGUE)

19:12.276 --> 19:14.813
Okay, where's the fridge?

19:18.658 --> 19:20.398
SARAH: Please, allow me.

19:21.118 --> 19:23.404
There 's cold beer
available on tap.

19:23.496 --> 19:26.033
Dr. Fargo says
you like baseball.

19:26.123 --> 19:28.079
I recorded
the Indiana game for you.

19:28.167 --> 19:29.327
Really?

